body_text.text:
A significant duration and level of exposure to a recognized carcinogen such as asbestos, hexavalent chromium (as in chromate production and the pigment industry), soluble radon compounds or radon gas, polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons, chloromethyl ethers, arsenic, or silica can increase the risk of lung cancer (Chapter 197). Such a history should be elicited in all patients. The International Agency for Research on Cancer provides a listing of occupational lung carcinogens and the likelihood of their association with cancer (
http://monographs.iarc.fr/ENG/Monographs/PDFs/index.php
).
